 Features
----------

   DOCX processing – reads and writes .docx files (ZIP archives) and replaces placeholders in text files like document.xml, headers, footers, comments, etc.
   Custom placeholder syntax – configure the prefix, suffix, and escape character.
   Multiple processing modes – Lenient (skip missing placeholders), Warn (log warnings), Strict (fail on missing placeholders).
   XML escaping – automatically escapes &, <, >, ", ' in replacements to keep the XML valid.
   Security – path traversal prevention, maximum file size, basic DOCX structure validation.
   Extensible – implement your own PlaceholderResolver for any data source, or DocxHooks for custom logic before/after processing.
   Indonesian date formatting – built‑in utilities to format dates in Indonesian (e.g., “26 Maret 2026”).
   Logging – integrated with the tracing crate.
   Serde support – configuration can be loaded from TOML or JSON files.
   No unsafe code – linted with forbid(unsafecode).

  

 Installation
---------------

Add this to your Cargo.toml:

    [dependencies]
    libplcdocx = "0.2.0"
    

If you need XML parsing (e.g., to manipulate the DOCX XML directly), enable the xml feature:

    libplcdocx = { version = "0.2.0", features = ["xml"] }
    

The default feature set includes config-helpers (which adds the optional dirs dependency). Disable default features if you don’t need that.

  

 Quick Start
--------------

    use libplcdocx::{Engine, Config, ProcessingMode};
    use std::collections::HashMap;
    use std::path::Path;
    
    fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn std::error::Error>> {
        // Create a configuration
        let config = Config::default()
            .withmode(ProcessingMode::Strict)
            .withlogging(true);
    
        // Build the engine
        let engine = Engine::new(config);
    
        // Prepare the placeholder mappings
        let mut mappings = HashMap::new();
        mappings.insert("NAME".tostring(), "John Doe".tostring());
        mappings.insert("DATE".tostring(), "26/03/2026".tostring());
    
        // Process the template
        engine.process(
            Path::new("template.docx"),
            Path::new("output.docx"),
            &mappings,
        )?;
    
        Ok(())
    }
    

This example replaces every occurrence of [[%%NAME%%]] with John Doe and [[%%DATE%%]] with 26/03/2026 (and automatically escapes XML special characters).

  

 Core Concepts
----------------

 Engine

The Engine is the main entry point. It holds the configuration, the parser, and optionally a custom resolver and hooks. It processes a DOCX file by walking through all ZIP entries, extracting text from relevant files, replacing placeholders, and writing back.

   Engine::new(config) creates a basic engine with a null resolver (fails to replace anything) and no hooks.
   Engine::withresolver() and Engine::withhooks() allow you to add your own logic.
   process() is a convenience method that takes a HashMap<String, String> as mappings.
   processwithresolver() uses the resolver already attached to the engine.

 Placeholder Parser

The PlaceholderParser is responsible for finding and replacing placeholders inside text. It uses the syntax defined in the configuration. The parser:

   Scans for the prefix and suffix.
   Extracts keys.
   Validates missing keys according to the processing mode.
   Performs replacements with XML escaping.

 Configuration

The Config struct controls almost every aspect of the engine:

   syntax: prefix, suffix, escape char.
   mode: lenient, warn, strict.
   dateformat and timeformat: used by the utility functions (Indonesian formatting).
   preservestyles: whether to preserve formatting (currently not implemented, but reserved).
   validate: perform extra DOCX validation.
   logging: enable internal logging.
   maxfilesize: maximum allowed DOCX file size.
   securitychecks: enable path traversal and empty‑file checks.

You can build a config fluently:

    let config = Config::default()
        .withplaceholderprefix("{{")?
        .withplaceholdersuffix("}}")?
        .withmode(ProcessingMode::Warn)
        .withlogging(true)
        .withmaxfilesize(100  1024  1024)
        .withsecuritychecks(true);
    

 Resolver

The PlaceholderResolver trait allows you to fetch replacement values from any source (database, API, file, etc.). It is asynchronous‑friendly and thread‑safe.

    pub trait PlaceholderResolver: Send + Sync {
        fn resolve(&self, key: &str, context: Option<&ProcessingContext>) -> Result<Option<String>>;
        fn resolvebatch(&self, keys: &[String], context: Option<&ProcessingContext>) -> Result<HashMap<String, String>> {
            // default implementation iterates over keys
        }
    }
    

   resolvebatch can be overridden for performance (e.g., batch fetch from database).
   The ProcessingContext gives you access to the current template path, output path, configuration, and the file being processed.

 Hooks

The DocxHooks trait lets you insert custom logic at various stages:

   onbeforeprocess – before reading the template.
   onafterfile – after each file in the ZIP archive is processed.
   onbeforewrite – before writing the final archive.
   onafterprocess – after everything is finished.

Hooks can modify the context (e.g., by adding user data) and can return errors to stop the pipeline.

 Processing Context

ProcessingContext carries information through the processing steps:

   templatepath and outputpath
   config (the engine’s config)
   currentfile – the ZIP entry being processed
   userdata – a place for hooks to store arbitrary data (e.g., to pass between hooks)

  

 Configuration Options
------------------------

 Placeholder Syntax

You can change the placeholder delimiters. The default is [[%% … %%]].

    let config = Config::default()
        .withplaceholderprefix("{{")?
        .withplaceholdersuffix("}}")?;
    

The escape character is currently unused but reserved for future escaping features.

 Processing Mode

   Lenient (default): missing placeholders are ignored (no replacement, no warning).
   Warn: missing placeholders are logged as warnings.
   Strict: missing placeholders cause an error.

    config.withmode(ProcessingMode::Strict);
    

 Date & Time Formatting

The library includes utility functions for formatting dates and times in Indonesian style. You can configure the date/time formats in Config, but they are mostly used by the example utilities.

    // In your own code, you can use these utils:
    use libplcdocx::utils::{formatdateindonesia, formattimerange};
    
    let date = formatdateindonesia("26/03/2026")?; // "26 Maret 2026"
    let timerange = formattimerange("10-14", "13:00 - 15:00 WIB")?; // "10:00 - 14:00 WIB"
    

 Security Settings

   maxfilesize: if a template is larger than this, processing fails.
   securitychecks: when enabled, the engine validates that all ZIP entry paths are relative and do not contain .. (path traversal). It also checks for an empty file and that required files like word/document.xml and [ContentTypes].xml exist.

  

 XML Escaping
----------------

Because DOCX files are XML‑based, any replacement value must be valid XML text. libplcdocx automatically escapes the following characters:

   & → &amp;
   < → &lt;
   > → &gt;
   " → &quot;
   ' → &apos;

You can also manually escape using libplcdocx::utils::escapexml.

  

 Error Handling
----------------

The library defines a comprehensive Error enum:

   FileNotFound
   InvalidDocx
   Zip – from the zip crate
   Xml – (feature‑gated) from quick-xml
   PlaceholderNotFound
   ConfigError
   DateError / TimeError
   Io
   FileTooLarge
   SecurityViolation
   Custom

All operations return Result<T, Error>. You can use ? to propagate errors.

  

 Advanced Usage
-----------------

 Custom Resolver

    use libplcdocx::{PlaceholderResolver, ProcessingContext, Result};
    use std::collections::HashMap;
    
    struct DatabaseResolver;
    
    impl PlaceholderResolver for DatabaseResolver {
        fn resolve(&self, key: &str, context: Option<&ProcessingContext>) -> Result<Option<String>> {
            // Imagine a database lookup
            match key {
                "USERNAME" => Ok(Some("johndoe".tostring())),
                "EMAIL" => Ok(Some("john@example.com".tostring())),
                 => Ok(None),
            }
        }
    }
    
    let engine = Engine::new(Config::default())
        .withresolver(DatabaseResolver);
    
    engine.processwithresolver(
        Path::new("template.docx"),
        Path::new("output.docx"),
    )?;
    

 Custom Hooks

    use libplcdocx::{DocxHooks, ProcessingContext, HookResult};
    
    struct LoggingHooks;
    
    impl DocxHooks for LoggingHooks {
        fn onbeforeprocess(&self, ctx: &ProcessingContext) -> HookResult {
            println!("Processing {}", ctx.templatepath.display());
            Ok(())
        }
    
        fn onafterfile(&self, ctx: &ProcessingContext, modified: bool) -> HookResult {
            if modified {
                println!("File {} was modified", ctx.currentfile);
            }
            Ok(())
        }
    
        fn onafterprocess(&self, ctx: &ProcessingContext) -> HookResult {
            println!("Finished processing");
            Ok(())
        }
    }
    
    let engine = Engine::new(Config::default())
        .withhooks(LoggingHooks);
    

 Batch Processing with Multiple Mappings

You can reuse the same engine with different mapping sets:

    let engine = Engine::new(config);
    let mappings1 = HashMap::from([("NAME", "Alice")]);
    engine.process(&template, &out1, &mappings1)?;
    
    let mappings2 = HashMap::from([("NAME", "Bob")]);
    engine.process(&template, &out2, &mappings2)?;
    

If you need more complex logic, attach a resolver that holds the mappings.

  

 Examples
-----------

 Load configuration from a file

    use libplcdocx::Config;
    
    // config.toml
    let config = Config::fromtoml("config.toml")?;
    
    // config.json
    let config = Config::fromjson("config.json")?;
    

Example TOML file:

    mode = "Strict"
    logging = true
    maxfilesize = 52428800   50 MiB
    securitychecks = true
    
    [syntax]
    prefix = "[[%%"
    suffix = "%%]]"
    escape = "\\"
    
    [dateformat]
    inputformat = "%d/%m/%Y"
    outputformat = "%d %B %Y"
    indonesialocale = true
    
    [timeformat]
    separator = "-"
    minuteseparator = "."
    outputformat = "{from} - {to} {tz}"
    defaultrange = "13:00 - 15:00 WIB"
    timezone = "WIB"
    

 Using built‑in Indonesian date utilities

    use libplcdocx::utils::{gettodayindonesia, getcurrentdatetimeindonesia};
    
    let today = gettodayindonesia()?; // "26 Maret 2026"
    let now = getcurrentdatetimeindonesia()?; // "26 Maret 2026 pukul 15:30"
    

  

 API Reference
----------------

The API is fully documented in the source code. For the most detailed and up‑to‑date information, run cargo doc --open after cloning the repository.

Key modules:

   libplcdocx::core – engine and parser.
   libplcdocx::framework – resolver, hooks, context.
   libplcdocx::handler – config, errors, types.
   libplcdocx::utils – helper functions (escape, date formatting).

  

